How does Shakespeare present ideas about appearance and reality in ?
Macbeth
Write about:
how ideas about appearance and reality are presented in this extract
how ideas about appearance and reality are presented elsewhere in the play.
In ‘Macbeth’, Shakespeare presents appearance and reality as separate but related
concepts, as several characters manipulate appearances to disguise the reality of their
intentions. In the extract, Lady Macbeth is attempting to convince Macbeth to betray
Duncan. Her use of gurative language in the extract shows how a person’s appearance
can be used to hide their real intentions. Elsewhere in the play, the complex relationship
between appearance and reality is explored through the Witches’ use of ambiguous language
and Macbeth’s visions. This atmosphere of confusion and deception leaves both the
characters and the audience questioning what is real and what is not.
In the extract, Macbeth’s outward appearance and his inner reality are aligned. Lady
Macbeth acknowledges this when she describes his face as a “book” in which “men / May
read strange matters”. This metaphor suggests that, for Macbeth at this point in the play,
appearance and reality are one and the same, as his real intentions can be read as easily
as words on a page. Up until this point, Macbeth has been loyal to Duncan, and he hasn’t
yet learned to hide behind false appearances. This implies that trustworthiness can be
determined by whether or not someone’s appearance reects their reality.
Lady Macbeth’s use of gurative language in the extract emphasises how appearance
can disguise reality. She tells Macbeth to “look like th’innocent ower, / But be the
serpent under’t.” Flowers carry connotations of purity and snakes are often associated with
evil, so by juxtaposing these two contrasting images, Shakespeare encourages the audience
to reect on the extent to which appearance and reality can differ. This quote links to the
Bible story of the Garden of Eden, in which Satan disguised himself as a snake to trick
Eve. This foreshadows how Macbeth will ‘disguise’ himself as a loyal thane to kill Duncan.
